steps.output:
Got it — test acknowledged.

I don’t yet have any code to analyze. Tell me where the code is (Git URL, upload a zip, or paste files), and I’ll produce a CodeGraph extraction.  

What I will return
- files: list of files with paths + types (source/test/config)
- symbols: top-level symbols (classes, functions, modules) and their locations
- routes: API endpoints / UI routes (if web app)
- libraries: third-party deps (from package.json / requirements.txt / go.mod, etc.)
- subsystems: inferred boundaries (e.g., auth, payments, UI, backend)
- dependencies: file/module-level dependency edges
- call structure: call graph for exported/public functions/handlers

Example output format (JSON-like)
{
  "files": [
    { "path": "src/server.js", "type": "source", "size": 4320 },
    { "path": "src/auth.js", "type": "source", "size": 2100 }
  ],
  "symbols": [
    { "name": "startServer", "type": "function", "file": "src/server.js", "line": 10 },
    { "name": "AuthService", "type": "class", "file": "src/auth.js", "line": 1 }
  ],
  "routes": [
    { "method": "POST", "path": "/login", "handler": "AuthService.login", "file": "src/auth.js", "line": 42 }
  ],
  "libraries": [
    { "name": "express", "version": "4.17.1" },
    { "name": "jsonwebtoken", "version": "8.5.1" }
  ],
  "subsystems": [
    { "name": "auth", "files": ["src/auth.js","src/session.js"] },
    { "name": "api", "files": ["src/server.js","src/routes/*.js"] }
  ],
  "dependencies": [
    { "from": "src/server.js", "to": "src/auth.js", "type": "import" },
    { "from": "src/auth.js", "to": "node_modules/jsonwebtoken", "type": "require" }
  ],
  "call_graph": [
    { "caller": "startServer", "callee": "AuthService.login", "via": "express route /login" }
  ]
}

Next steps — please provide one of:
- Git repo URL (public or credentials)
- Zip/tar upload of source
- Paste a file tree or specific files to analyze

If you just wanted to verify connectivity, say “analyze sample” and I’ll run a tiny demo extraction. Which would you like?

